muros (0.9.22) trixie; urgency=medium

  * Ported the SSH daemon configuration (openssh.inc) from FreeBSD to Debian, so
    the System: Settings: Administration options (port, root login, password
    authentication, listen interfaces, ciphers/MACs/KEX/host-key algorithms) now
    actually reconfigure sshd. Settings are written to a drop-in at
    /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/muros.conf that the stock Debian sshd_config already
    includes; the main config and package-managed host keys are left untouched.
    The generated config is validated with "sshd -t" before being applied and is
    rolled back on failure, and the daemon is reloaded (not restarted) to keep
    existing sessions, all to avoid locking the box out. Service control now goes
    through systemd (ssh.service) instead of pkill.

 -- MurOS <dev@muros.org>  Sat, 20 Jun 2026 17:05:00 +0200

